generate_linear_model_html[source]

generate_linear_model_html(model, feature_names:Iterable[str], target_name:str, intercept_formatter:str='.2f', coef_formatter:str='.2f')

Generate an HTML equation that characterizes a linear model.

Model components are color-coded as follows:

  • target: red
  • intercept: purple
  • coefficients: green
  • features: blue

Parameters:

  • model: fitted scikit-learn linear model of the form y = b0 + b1 * x1 + ....
  • feature_names: feature names in the order in which they were given to the model.
  • target_name : Name of target variable y
  • intercept_formatter: Format specifier for model intercept
  • coef_formatter: Format specifier for model coefficients
{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
X_diabetes, y_diabetes = sklearn.datasets.load_diabetes(return_X_y=True, as_frame=True)

HTML(
    generate_linear_model_html(
        model=LinearRegression().fit(X_diabetes, y_diabetes),
        feature_names=X_diabetes.columns,
        target_name="progression",
    )
)
progression = 152.13 - 10.01 * age - 239.82 * sex + 519.84 * bmi + 324.39 * bp - 792.18 * s1 + 476.75 * s2 + 101.04 * s3 + 177.06 * s4 + 751.28 * s5 + 67.63 * s6

generate_logistic_model_html[source]

generate_logistic_model_html(model, feature_names:Iterable[str], target_val_names:Iterable[str], intercept_formatter:str='.2f', coef_formatter:str='.2f')

Generate an HTML equation that characterizes a logistic regression model.

Model components are color-coded as follows:

  • target: red
  • intercept: purple
  • coefficients: green
  • features: blue

Parameters:

  • model: fitted scikit-learn linear model of the form log-odds(y) = b0 + b1 * x1 + ....
  • feature_names: feature names in the order in which they were given to the model.
  • target_val_names: Names of the values of the target variable
  • intercept_formatter: Format specifier for model intercept
  • coef_formatter: Format specifier for model coefficients
{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
iris = sklearn.datasets.load_iris()
X_iris, y_iris = iris["data"], iris["target"]
y_iris = pd.Series(y_iris).map(
    {num: name for num, name in zip([0, 1, 2], iris["target_names"])}
)
X_iris = pd.DataFrame(X_iris, columns=iris["feature_names"])

lr_iris = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1_000).fit(X_iris, y_iris)
HTML(
    generate_logistic_model_html(
        model=lr_iris,
        feature_names=X_iris.columns,
        target_val_names=y_iris.unique(),
    )
)

log-odds(setosa) = 9.85 - 0.42 * sepal length (cm) + 0.97 * sepal width (cm) - 2.52 * petal length (cm) - 1.08 * petal width (cm)

log-odds(versicolor) = 2.24 + 0.53 * sepal length (cm) - 0.32 * sepal width (cm) - 0.21 * petal length (cm) - 0.94 * petal width (cm)

log-odds(virginica) = -12.09 - 0.11 * sepal length (cm) - 0.65 * sepal width (cm) + 2.72 * petal length (cm) + 2.02 * petal width (cm)

plot_2d_regression[source]

plot_2d_regression(model, X:DataFrame, y:Union[array, Series], cmap='viridis', tick_formatter:str='.2f', ax=None, plot_data:bool=True)

Plot data and predictions for regression model with two features

Parameters:

  • model: fitted scikit-learn regression model with two features
  • X: Feature matrix
  • y: Target values
  • cmap: Colormap
  • ticket_formatter: Tick label format specifier
  • ax: Matplotlib Axes object. Plot will be added to this object if provided; otherwise a new Axes object will be generated.
  • plot_data: Whether to plot the data points in addition to the model predictions.

plot_2d_regression_3d[source]

plot_2d_regression_3d(model, X:DataFrame, y:Union[array, Series], plot_data:bool=True, x0_density=10, x1_density=10, surf_kwargs={'alpha': 0.4, 'cmap': 'viridis'}, scatter_kwargs={}, ax=None)

Plot data and predictions for regression model with 2 features in 3D

Best viewed with a tool such as https://github.com/matplotlib/ipympl that supports rotating the output

Parameters:

  • model: fitted scikit-learn regression model with two features
  • X: Feature matrix
  • y: Target values
  • plot_data: Whether to plot the data points in addition to the model predictions.
  • x0_density: Number of points along first axis of grid for plotting surface
  • x1_density: Number of points along second axis of grid for plotting surface
  • surf_kwargs: kwargs to pass to the model prediction surface
  • scatter_kwargs: kwargs to pass to the scatter plot of the data
  • ax: Matplotlib Axes object. Plot will be added to this object if provided; otherwise a new Axes object will be generated.
{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
X = X_diabetes.loc[:, feature_cols].sample(50)
y = y_diabetes.loc[X.index]
ax = plot_2d_regression_3d(
    LinearRegression().fit(X, y), X, y, scatter_kwargs={"alpha": 1}
)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
from sklearn.svm import SVR

ax = plot_2d_regression_3d(SVR(kernel="poly").fit(X, y), X, y)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(2, 2))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection="3d")
ax = plot_2d_regression_3d(
    DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=3).fit(X, y),
    X,
    y,
    plot_data=False,
    surf_kwargs={"cmap": "Blues", "alpha": 0.8},
    ax=ax,
)

Plot data and predictions for classification model with two features

  • model: fitted scikit-learn classification model
  • X: Feature matrix with at least two columns. The first two columns will be used.

  • tick_formatter: Tick label format specifier

plot_2d_binary_classification_3d[source]

plot_2d_binary_classification_3d(model, X:DataFrame, y:Series, thresh=0.5, plot_prob:bool=True, plot_thresh:bool=True, plot_data:bool=True, x0_density=10, x1_density=10, prob_surf_kwargs={'alpha': 0.4, 'cmap': 'viridis'}, thresh_surf_kwargs={'alpha': 0.4}, scatter_kwargs={}, ax=None)

Plot data and predictions for binary classification model with 2 features in 3D

Best viewed with a tool such as https://github.com/matplotlib/ipympl that supports rotating the output

Parameters:

  • model: fitted scikit-learn regression model with two features
  • X: Feature matrix
  • y: Target values
  • thresh: Probability threshold for counting a prediction as positive
  • plot_prob: Whether to plot the model probabilities
  • plot_thresh: Whether to plot a classification threshold
  • plot_data: Whether to plot the data
  • x0_density: Number of points along first axis of grid for plotting surface
  • x1_density: Number of points along second axis of grid for plotting surface
  • prob_surf_kwargs: kwargs to pass to the model probability surface
  • thresh_surf_kwargs: kwargs to pass to the threshold surface
  • scatter_kwargs: kwargs to pass to the scatter plot of the data
  • ax: Matplotlib Axes object. Plot will be added to this object if provided; otherwise a new Axes object will be generated.
{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
X = X_iris.iloc[:, :2]
y = y_iris == "virginica"
y.name = "is-virginica"
ax = plot_2d_binary_classification_3d(LogisticRegression().fit(X, y), X, y)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
X = X_cancer.iloc[:, :2]
y = y_cancer

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection="3d")

ax = plot_2d_binary_classification_3d(DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2).fit(X, y), X, y, thresh=0.2, plot_thresh=False, plot_data=False, prob_surf_kwargs={"alpha": 1, "cmap": "Greens"}, ax=ax)

plot_linear_coefs_vs_hparam(model, X:DataFrame, y:Sequence, hparam:str, hparam_vals:Sequence[float])

Plot linear regression coefficients against a hyperparameter

Parameters:

  • model: fitted scikit-learn linear model of the form y = b0 + b1 * x1 + ....
  • X: Feature matrix
  • y: Target values
  • hparam: Name of hyperparameter
  • hparam_vals: Values of hyperparameter to use
{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
ax = plot_linear_coefs_vs_hparam(
    model=Ridge(),
    X=X_diabetes,
    y=y_diabetes,
    hparam="alpha",
    hparam_vals=np.logspace(-2, 0.5, 20),
)

grid_ridge_diabetes = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=Ridge(),
    param_grid={"alpha": np.logspace(-2, -0.8, 20)},
    cv=KFold(10, shuffle=True, random_state=2),
)
grid_ridge_diabetes.fit(X_diabetes, y_diabetes)
# fmt: off
ax.axvline(grid_ridge_diabetes.best_params_["alpha"], c="k");
